# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-gke
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:gcp-gke/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] A **computer cluster** is a group of autonomous computers that work together so that they can be viewed as a single system.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Unlike grid computers, computer clusters have each node set to perform the same task, controlled and scheduled by software.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The newest manifestation of cluster computing is cloud computing.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The components of a cluster are usually connected to each other through fast local area networks, with each node (computer used as a server) running its own instance of an operating system.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In most circumstances, all of the nodes use the same hardware and the same operating system, although in some setups (e.g. using Open Source Cluster Application Resources (OSCAR)), different operating systems can be used on each computer, or different hardware.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Clusters are usually deployed to improve performance and availability over that of a single computer, while typically being much more cost-effective than single computers of comparable speed or availability.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Computer clusters emerged as a result of the convergence of a number of computing trends including the availability of low-cost microprocessors, high-speed networks, and software for high-performance distributed computing.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] They have a wide range of applicability and deployment, ranging from small business clusters with a handful of nodes to some of the fastest supercomputers in the world such as IBM's Sequoia.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Prior to the advent of clusters, single-unit fault tolerant mainframes with modular redundancy were employed; but the lower upfront cost of clusters, and increased speed of network fabric has favoured the adoption of clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In contrast to high-reliability mainframes, clusters are cheaper to scale out, but also have increased complexity in error handling, as in clusters error modes are not opaque to running programs.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The desire to get more computing power and better reliability by orchestrating a number of low-cost commercial off-the-shelf computers has given rise to a variety of architectures and configurations.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The computer clustering approach usually (but not always) connects a number of readily available computing nodes (e.g. personal computers used as servers) via a fast local area network.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The activities of the computing nodes are orchestrated by "clustering middleware", a software layer that sits atop the nodes and allows the users to treat the cluster as by and large one cohesive computing unit, e.g. via a single system image concept.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Computer clustering relies on a centralized management approach which makes the nodes available as orchestrated shared servers.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] It is distinct from other approaches such as peer-to-peer or grid computing which also use many nodes, but with a far more distributed nature.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] A computer cluster may be a simple two-node system which just connects two personal computers, or may be a very fast supercomputer.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] A basic approach to building a cluster is that of a Beowulf cluster which may be built with a few personal computers to produce a cost-effective alternative to traditional high-performance computing.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] An early project that showed the viability of the concept was the 133-node Stone Soupercomputer.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The developers used Linux, the Parallel Virtual Machine toolkit and the Message Passing Interface library to achieve high performance at a relatively low cost.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Although a cluster may consist of just a few personal computers connected by a simple network, the cluster architecture may also be used to achieve very high levels of performance.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The TOP500 organization's semiannual list of the 500 fastest supercomputers often includes many clusters, e.g. the world's fastest machine in 2011 was the K computer which has a distributed memory, cluster architecture.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Greg Pfister has stated that clusters were not invented by any specific vendor but by customers who could not fit all their work on one computer, or needed a backup.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Pfister estimates the date as some time in the 1960s.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The formal engineering basis of cluster computing as a means of doing parallel work of any sort was arguably invented by Gene Amdahl of IBM, who in 1967 published what has come to be regarded as the seminal paper on parallel processing: Amdahl's Law.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The history of early computer clusters is more or less directly tied to the history of early networks, as one of the primary motivations for the development of a network was to link computing resources, creating a de facto computer cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The first production system designed as a cluster was the Burroughs B5700 in the mid-1960s.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This allowed up to four computers, each with either one or two processors, to be tightly coupled to a common disk storage subsystem in order to distribute the workload.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Unlike standard multiprocessor systems, each computer could be restarted without disrupting overall operation.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In the early-to-mid-1970s, the General Electric Mark II adopted a high-reliability cluster technology, in which up to eight processing systems (each with its own copy of the operating system) had access to multiple file systems with file-level locking.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In 1984, AT&T released its B3 series computers including a fault-tolerant clustered computing system of two processors.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Clustering per se did not really take off until Digital Equipment Corporation released their VAXcluster product in 1984 for the VMS operating system which, unlike earlier manufacturers, used the term "cluster" in its marketing.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The Tandem NonStop, ARC and VAXcluster products not only supported parallel computing, but also shared file systems and peripheral devices.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The idea was to provide the advantages of parallel processing, while maintaining data reliability and uniqueness.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Another noteworthy commercial cluster was the *IBM S/390 Parallel Sysplex* (circa 1994, primarily for business use).
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Within the same time frame, while computer clusters used parallelism outside the computer on a commodity network, supercomputers began to use them within the same computer.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Following the success of the CDC 6600 in 1964, the Cray 1 was delivered in 1976, and introduced internal parallelism via vector processing.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] While early supercomputers excluded clusters and relied on shared memory, in time some of the fastest supercomputers (e.g. the K computer) relied on cluster architectures.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Clusters were used for the majority of the world's automated teller machine transactions, credit cards, emergency 911 calls, stock exchanges, largest data warehouses and more by the 1990s if not earlier.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Computer clusters may be configured for different purposes ranging from general purpose business needs such as web-service support, to computation-intensive scientific calculations.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In either case, the cluster may use a high-availability approach.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Note that the attributes described below are not exclusive and a "computer cluster" may also use a high-availability approach, etc.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] "Load-balancing" clusters are configurations in which cluster-nodes share computational workload to provide better overall performance.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] For example, a web server cluster may assign different queries to different nodes, so the overall response time will be optimized.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Computer clusters are used for computation-intensive purposes, rather than handling IO-oriented operations such as web service or databases.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] For instance, a computer cluster might support computational simulations of vehicle crashes or weather.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Very tightly coupled computer clusters are designed for work that may approach "supercomputing".
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] "High-availability clusters" (also known as failover clusters, or HA clusters) improve the availability of the cluster approach.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] They operate by having redundant nodes, which are then used to provide service when system components fail.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] HA cluster implementations attempt to use redundancy of cluster components to eliminate single points of failure.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] There are commercial implementations of High-Availability clusters for many operating systems.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The Linux-HA project is one commonly used free software HA package for the Linux operating system.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Scalability is enhanced by adding systems to a cluster, which is the primary basis of massive parallelism.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Unlike symmetric multi-processor systems, where scalability eventually fades as more processors are added (and thus either becomes more expensive or not scalable enough), whereas, for some applications, scalability can be maintained in a loosely-coupled cluster system.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This scalability may require cluster-aware middleware or database to work well.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Clusters are primarily designed with performance in mind, but installations are based on many other factors.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Fault tolerance (*the ability of a system to continue operating despite a malfunctioning node*) enables scalability, and in high-performance situations, allows for a low frequency of maintenance routines, resource consolidation (e.g., RAID), and centralized management.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Advantages include enabling data recovery in the event of a disaster and providing parallel data processing and high processing capacity.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In terms of scalability, clusters provide this in their ability to add nodes horizontally.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This means that more computers may be added to the cluster, to improve its performance, redundancy and fault tolerance.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This can be an inexpensive solution for a higher performing cluster compared to scaling up a single node in the cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This property of computer clusters can allow for larger computational loads to be executed by a larger number of lower performing computers.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] When adding a new node to a cluster, reliability increases because the entire cluster does not need to be taken down.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] A single node can be taken down for maintenance, while the rest of the cluster takes on the load of that individual node.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] If a large number of computers are clustered together, this lends itself to the use of distributed file systems and RAID, both of which can increase the reliability and speed of a cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] One of the issues in designing a cluster is how tightly coupled the individual nodes may be.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] For instance, a single computer job may require frequent communication among nodes: this implies that the cluster shares a dedicated network, is densely located, and probably has homogeneous nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The other extreme is where a computer job uses one or few nodes, and needs little or no inter-node communication, approaching grid computing.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In a Beowulf cluster, the application programs never see the computational nodes (also called slave computers) but only interact with the "Master" which is a specific computer handling the scheduling and management of the slaves.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In a typical implementation the Master has two network interfaces, one that communicates with the private Beowulf network for the slaves, the other for the general purpose network of the organization.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The slave computers typically have their own version of the same operating system, and local memory and disk space.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] However, the private slave network may also have a large and shared file server that stores global persistent data, accessed by the slaves as needed.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] A special purpose 144-node DEGIMA cluster is tuned to running astrophysical N-body simulations using the Multiple-Walk parallel tree code, rather than general purpose scientific computations.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Due to the increasing computing power of each generation of game consoles, a novel use has emerged where they are repurposed into High-performance computing (HPC) clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Some examples of game console clusters are Sony PlayStation clusters and Microsoft Xbox clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Another example of consumer game product is the Nvidia Tesla Personal Supercomputer workstation, which uses multiple graphics accelerator processor chips.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Besides game consoles, high-end graphics cards too can be used instead.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The use of graphics cards (or rather their GPU's) to do calculations for grid computing is vastly more economical than using CPU's, despite being less precise.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] However, when using double-precision values, they become as precise to work with as CPU's and are still much less costly (purchase cost).
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Computer clusters have historically run on separate physical computers with the same operating system.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] With the advent of virtualization, the cluster nodes may run on separate physical computers with different operating systems which are painted above with a virtual layer to look similar.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The cluster may also be virtualized on various configurations as maintenance takes place; an example implementation is Xen as the virtualization manager with Linux-HA.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] As the computer clusters were appearing during the 1980s, so were supercomputers.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] One of the elements that distinguished the three classes at that time was that the early supercomputers relied on shared memory.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Clusters do not typically use physically shared memory, while many supercomputer architectures have also abandoned it.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] However, the use of a clustered file system is essential in modern computer clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Examples include the IBM General Parallel File System, Microsoft's Cluster Shared Volumes or the Oracle Cluster File System.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Two widely used approaches for communication between cluster nodes are MPI (Message Passing Interface) and PVM (Parallel Virtual Machine).
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] PVM was developed at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory around 1989 before MPI was available.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] PVM must be directly installed on every cluster node and provides a set of software libraries that paint the node as a "parallel virtual machine".
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] PVM provides a run-time environment for message-passing, task and resource management, and fault notification.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] PVM can be used by user programs written in C, C++, or Fortran, etc.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] MPI emerged in the early 1990s out of discussions among 40 organizations.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The initial effort was supported by ARPA and National Science Foundation.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Rather than starting anew, the design of MPI drew on various features available in commercial systems of the time.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The MPI specifications then gave rise to specific implementations.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] MPI implementations typically use TCP/IP and socket connections.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] MPI is now a widely available communications model that enables parallel programs to be written in languages such as C, Fortran, Python, etc.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Thus, unlike PVM which provides a concrete implementation, MPI is a specification which has been implemented in systems such as MPICH and Open MPI.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] One of the challenges in the use of a computer cluster is the cost of administrating it which can at times be as high as the cost of administrating N independent machines, if the cluster has N nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In some cases this provides an advantage to shared memory architectures with lower administration costs.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This has also made virtual machines popular, due to the ease of administration.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] When a large multi-user cluster needs to access very large amounts of data, task scheduling becomes a challenge.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] In a heterogeneous CPU-GPU cluster with a complex application environment, the performance of each job depends on the characteristics of the underlying cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Therefore, mapping tasks onto CPU cores and GPU devices provides significant challenges.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This is an area of ongoing research; algorithms that combine and extend MapReduce and Hadoop have been proposed and studied.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] When a node in a cluster fails, strategies such as "fencing" may be employed to keep the rest of the system operational.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Fencing is the process of isolating a node or protecting shared resources when a node appears to be malfunctioning.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] There are two classes of fencing methods; one disables a node itself, and the other disallows access to resources such as shared disks.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The STONITH method stands for "Shoot The Other Node In The Head", meaning that the suspected node is disabled or powered off.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] For instance, *power fencing* uses a power controller to turn off an inoperable node.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The *resources fencing* approach disallows access to resources without powering off the node.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This may include *persistent reservation fencing* via the SCSI3, fibre channel fencing to disable the fibre channel port, or global network block device (GNBD) fencing to disable access to the GNBD server.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] However, "computer clusters" which perform complex computations for a small number of users need to take advantage of the parallel processing capabilities of the cluster and partition "the same computation" among several nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Automatic parallelization of programs remains a technical challenge, but parallel programming models can be used to effectuate a higher degree of parallelism via the simultaneous execution of separate portions of a program on different processors.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Developing and debugging parallel programs on a cluster requires parallel language primitives and suitable tools such as those discussed by the *High Performance Debugging Forum* (HPDF) which resulted in the HPD specifications.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Tools such as TotalView were then developed to debug parallel implementations on computer clusters which use Message Passing Interface (MPI) or Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) for message passing.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The University of California, Berkeley *Network of Workstations* (NOW) system gathers cluster data and stores them in a database, while a system such as PARMON, developed in India, allows visually observing and managing large clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Application checkpointing can be used to restore a given state of the system when a node fails during a long multi-node computation.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] This is essential in large clusters, given that as the number of nodes increases, so does the likelihood of node failure under heavy computational loads.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Checkpointing can restore the system to a stable state so that processing can resume without needing to recompute results.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] The Linux world supports various cluster software; for application clustering, there is distcc, and MPICH.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Linux Virtual Server, Linux-HA – director-based clusters that allow incoming requests for services to be distributed across multiple cluster nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] MOSIX, LinuxPMI, Kerrighed, OpenSSI are full-blown clusters integrated into the kernel that provide for automatic process migration among homogeneous nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] OpenSSI, openMosix and Kerrighed are single-system image implementations.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Microsoft Windows Cluster Server software, based on the Windows Server platform, originally released in 1997/98, provides cluster support for high-performance computing including the job scheduler, MSMPI library and management tools.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] gLite is a set of middleware technologies created by the Enabling Grids for E-sciencE (EGEE) project.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] slurm is also used to schedule and manage some of the largest supercomputer clusters (see top500 list).
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] Although most computer clusters are permanent fixtures, attempts at flash mob computing have been made to build short-lived clusters for specific computations.
[src:gcp-gke/cluster-computing] However, larger-scale volunteer computing systems such as BOINC-based systems have had more followers.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:gcp-gke/container-orchestration] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] Google Cloud provides infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and serverless computing environments.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] In April 2008, Google announced App Engine, a platform for developing and hosting web applications in Google-managed data centers, which was the first cloud computing service from the company.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] The service became generally available in November 2011.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] Since the announcement of App Engine, Google added multiple cloud services to the platform.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] Google lists over 100 products under the Google Cloud brand.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] Some of the key services are listed below.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] A region is a specific geographical location where users can deploy cloud resources.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] Each region is an independent geographic area that consists of zones.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] A zone is a deployment area for Google Cloud Platform resources within a region.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] Zones should be considered a single failure domain within a region.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] As of Q1 2024, Google Cloud Platform is available in 40 regions and 121 zones.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] For those familiar with other notable cloud service providers, a comparison of similar services may be helpful in understanding Google Cloud Platform's offerings.
[src:gcp-gke/google-cloud-platform] Customers announced in 2023 include Kingfisher plc, the Government of Kuwait, Deutsche Börse Group, Unity Technologies, Uber, FanCode, Daimler, and Wix.com.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:gcp-gke/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] A managed IT services provider is a third-party service provider that proactively monitors & manages a customer's server/network/system infrastructure, cybersecurity and end-user systems against a clearly defined Service Level Agreement (SLA).
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] Small and medium-sized businesses (SMBs), nonprofits and government agencies hire MSPs to perform a defined set of day-to-day management services so they can focus on their core businesses with reduced risk of extended system downtime or service interruptions.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] These services may include network and infrastructure management, security and monitoring.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] Most MSPs bill an upfront setup or transition fee and an ongoing flat or near-fixed monthly fee, which benefits clients by providing them with predictable IT support costs.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] Sometimes MSPs act as facilitators who manage and procure staffing services on behalf of the client.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] In such context, they may use a vendor management system (VMS) for transparency and efficiency.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] A managed service provider may also help a business create IT disaster recovery plans.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] The evolution of MSP started in the 1990s with the emergence of application service providers (ASPs) who helped pave the way for remote support for IT infrastructure.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] From the initial focus of remote monitoring and management of servers and networks, the scope of an MSP's services expanded to include mobile device management, managed security, remote firewall administration and security-as-a-service, and managed print services.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] The first books on the topic of managed services - *Service Agreements for SMB Consultants: A Quick-Start Guide to Managed Services* and *The Guide to a Successful Managed Services Practice* - were published in 2006 by Palachuk and Simpson, respectively.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] Since then, the managed services business model has gained ground among enterprise-level companies.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] As the value-added reseller (VAR) community evolved to a higher level of services, it adapted the managed service model and tailored it to SMB companies.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] As the IT infrastructure components of many SMB and large corporations are migrating to the cloud, with MSPs (managed services providers) increasingly facing the challenge of cloud computing, a number of MSPs are providing in-house cloud services or acting as brokers with cloud services providers.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] A recent survey claims that a lack of knowledge and expertise in cloud computing rather than client's reluctance, appears to be the main obstacle to this transition.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] The most common managed services revolve around IT: connectivity and bandwidth, network monitoring, security, virtualization, and disaster recovery.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] Attackers have compromised MSPs and software used by MSPs as a form of supply chain attack.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] National Cybersecurity and Communications Integration Center (NCCIC) warned the public that it knew of attackers, including advanced persistent threats, attempting to infiltrate the networks of MSPs as a way to conduct cyber espionage and intellectual property theft.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] NCCIC said that this type of attack, which dated to at least 2016, targeted MSPs because compromising them could allow attackers to access customer networks.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] By 2019, attackers began targeting MSPs to spread ransomware because hacking into a MSP could allow them to install ransomware in many MSP client systems.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] Attackers found and exploited vulnerabilities in software used by MSPs, such as remote monitoring and management products.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] In the July 2021 Kaseya VSA ransomware attack, the REvil criminal organization exploited a vulnerability in Kaseya software to attack its MSP customers with ransomware and up 1,500 companies that were clients of the MSPs.
[src:gcp-gke/managed-services] In 2025, the DragonForce ransomware group attacked a MSP and used its remote monitoring and management platform to steal client data and encrypt client systems.
